        <div class="slide">
            <h1>AAA - Authentication, Authorization, and Accounting</h1>

            <div style="max-width: 1000px; margin: 0 auto;">
                <p style="font-size: 1.4em; text-align: center; margin-bottom: 50px; background: linear-gradient(135deg, #0a192f 0%, #112240 100%); color: white; padding: 30px; border-radius: 12px;">
                    The <strong style="color: #00d9ff;">AAA framework</strong> is the security model that controls access to computer resources, enforces policies, and audits usage.
                </p>

                <div style="margin-bottom: 50px;">
                    <div style="background: #f8fafc; padding: 35px; border-radius: 12px; border-left: 8px solid #00d9ff; margin-bottom: 30px;">
                        <h2 style="color: #0a192f; margin-top: 0; font-size: 2.2em;">üîê Authentication - "Who are you?"</h2>
                        <p style="font-size: 1.3em; margin-bottom: 20px; color: #0a192f;">
                            <strong>Definition:</strong> The process of verifying the identity of a user, device, or system.
                        </p>
                        <h4 style="color: #0a192f; font-size: 1.3em; margin-top: 25px;">Authentication Factors:</h4>
                        <ul style="font-size: 1.2em; line-height: 1.9;">
                            <li><strong style="color: #00d9ff;">Something You Know:</strong> Passwords, PINs, security questions</li>
                            <li><strong style="color: #00d9ff;">Something You Have:</strong> Smart cards, tokens, mobile phones (OTP codes)</li>
                            <li><strong style="color: #00d9ff;">Something You Are:</strong> Biometrics - fingerprint, facial recognition, retina scan</li>
                            <li><strong style="color: #00d9ff;">Somewhere You Are:</strong> Location-based (GPS, IP address)</li>
                            <li><strong style="color: #00d9ff;">Something You Do:</strong> Behavioral biometrics - typing patterns, gait analysis</li>
                        </ul>
                        <h4 style="color: #0a192f; font-size: 1.3em; margin-top: 25px;">Multi-Factor Authentication (MFA):</h4>
                        <p style="font-size: 1.2em;">Combining two or more factors for stronger security (e.g., password + fingerprint + SMS code)</p>
                        <div style="background: linear-gradient(135deg, #0a192f 0%, #112240 100%); color: white; padding: 20px; border-radius: 8px; margin-top: 20px;">
                            <strong style="color: #00d9ff;">Real-World Example:</strong> When you log into your bank app, you enter a password (what you know) and then receive a code on your phone (what you have) - that's 2FA!
                        </div>
                    </div>

                    <div style="background: #f8fafc; padding: 35px; border-radius: 12px; border-left: 8px solid #00d9ff; margin-bottom: 30px;">
                        <h2 style="color: #0a192f; margin-top: 0; font-size: 2.2em;">üõ°Ô∏è Authorization - "What can you do?"</h2>
                        <p style="font-size: 1.3em; margin-bottom: 20px; color: #0a192f;">
                            <strong>Definition:</strong> Determining what an authenticated user is allowed to access and what actions they can perform.
                        </p>
                        <h4 style="color: #0a192f; font-size: 1.3em; margin-top: 25px;">Authorization Models:</h4>
                        <ul style="font-size: 1.2em; line-height: 1.9;">
                            <li><strong style="color: #00d9ff;">Discretionary Access Control (DAC):</strong> Resource owners decide who gets access (file permissions)</li>
                            <li><strong style="color: #00d9ff;">Mandatory Access Control (MAC):</strong> System-enforced policies, used in military/government (security clearance levels)</li>
                            <li><strong style="color: #00d9ff;">Role-Based Access Control (RBAC):</strong> Access based on user roles in the organization</li>
                            <li><strong style="color: #00d9ff;">Attribute-Based Access Control (ABAC):</strong> Access based on attributes (user, resource, environment)</li>
                        </ul>
                        <h4 style="color: #0a192f; font-size: 1.3em; margin-top: 25px;">Key Concepts:</h4>
                        <p style="font-size: 1.2em; margin-bottom: 10px;"><strong style="color: #00d9ff;">Read, Write, Execute:</strong> Basic permission types for files and resources</p>
                        <p style="font-size: 1.2em;"><strong style="color: #00d9ff;">Implicit Deny:</strong> If not explicitly allowed, access is denied by default</p>
                        <div style="background: linear-gradient(135deg, #0a192f 0%, #112240 100%); color: white; padding: 20px; border-radius: 8px; margin-top: 20px;">
                            <strong style="color: #00d9ff;">Real-World Example:</strong> In a company, an HR employee can view and edit employee records, but a sales employee can only view their own profile - that's authorization!
                        </div>
                    </div>

                    <div style="background: #f8fafc; padding: 35px; border-radius: 12px; border-left: 8px solid #00d9ff;">
                        <h2 style="color: #0a192f; margin-top: 0; font-size: 2.2em;">üìä Accounting - "What did you do?"</h2>
                        <p style="font-size: 1.3em; margin-bottom: 20px; color: #0a192f;">
                            <strong>Definition:</strong> Tracking and logging user activities for auditing, billing, and security monitoring.
                        </p>
                        <h4 style="color: #0a192f; font-size: 1.3em; margin-top: 25px;">What Gets Tracked:</h4>
                        <ul style="font-size: 1.2em; line-height: 1.9;">
                            <li><strong style="color: #00d9ff;">Login/Logout Times:</strong> When users access and leave systems</li>
                            <li><strong style="color: #00d9ff;">Resources Accessed:</strong> Which files, databases, or systems were used</li>
                            <li><strong style="color: #00d9ff;">Actions Performed:</strong> File modifications, data downloads, configuration changes</li>
                            <li><strong style="color: #00d9ff;">Data Volume:</strong> How much bandwidth or storage was consumed</li>
                            <li><strong style="color: #00d9ff;">Failed Attempts:</strong> Unsuccessful login attempts, unauthorized access tries</li>
                            <li><strong style="color: #00d9ff;">Session Duration:</strong> How long users were connected</li>
                        </ul>
                        <h4 style="color: #0a192f; font-size: 1.3em; margin-top: 25px;">Why Accounting Matters:</h4>
                        <ul style="font-size: 1.2em; line-height: 1.9;">
                            <li><strong style="color: #00d9ff;">Security Forensics:</strong> Investigate incidents and identify attackers</li>
                            <li><strong style="color: #00d9ff;">Compliance:</strong> Meet regulatory requirements (GDPR, HIPAA, SOX)</li>
                            <li><strong style="color: #00d9ff;">Billing:</strong> Charge users based on resource consumption (cloud services)</li>
                            <li><strong style="color: #00d9ff;">Behavior Analysis:</strong> Detect anomalies and insider threats</li>
                        </ul>
                        <div style="background: linear-gradient(135deg, #0a192f 0%, #112240 100%); color: white; padding: 20px; border-radius: 8px; margin-top: 20px;">
                            <strong style="color: #00d9ff;">Real-World Example:</strong> When a data breach occurs, security teams review logs to see: Who accessed the data? When? From where? What did they do? All possible through accounting logs!
                        </div>
                    </div>
                </div>

                <h2 style="margin-top: 50px; text-align: center;">AAA Protocols & Technologies</h2>
                <div class="feature-grid">
                    <div class="feature-card">
                        <h4>üîµ RADIUS</h4>
                        <p>Remote Authentication Dial-In User Service - widely used for network access (WiFi, VPNs)</p>
                    </div>
                    <div class="feature-card">
                        <h4>üü¢ TACACS+</h4>
                        <p>Terminal Access Controller Access-Control System Plus - Cisco's protocol for device management</p>
                    </div>
                    <div class="feature-card">
                        <h4>üü° Kerberos</h4>
                        <p>Network authentication protocol using tickets - used in Windows Active Directory</p>
                    </div>
                    <div class="feature-card">
                        <h4>üü£ LDAP</h4>
                        <p>Lightweight Directory Access Protocol - directory services for user authentication</p>
                    </div>
                    <div class="feature-card">
                        <h4>üî¥ OAuth 2.0</h4>
                        <p>Authorization framework for delegated access - "Sign in with Google/Facebook"</p>
                    </div>
                    <div class="feature-card">
                        <h4>üü† SAML</h4>
                        <p>Security Assertion Markup Language - enterprise SSO and federation</p>
                    </div>
                </div>

                <p style="font-size: 1.4em; text-align: center; margin-top: 50px; padding: 30px; background: linear-gradient(135deg, #0a192f 0%, #112240 100%); color: white; border-radius: 12px;">
                    <strong style="color: #00d9ff;">The AAA Flow:</strong> First authenticate who you are ‚Üí Then authorize what you can do ‚Üí Finally account for what you did. All three work together to create a secure access control system!
                </p>
            </div>
        </div>

        <!-- Slide 10 -->
        <div class="slide">
            <h1>Need to Know & Least Privilege</h1>

            <div style="max-width: 1000px; margin: 0 auto;">
                <p style="font-size: 1.3em; text-align: center; margin-bottom: 50px; background: linear-gradient(135deg, #0a192f 0%, #112240 100%); color: white; padding: 30px; border-radius: 12px;">
                    Two fundamental security principles that minimize risk by limiting access to only what is absolutely necessary for job functions.
                </p>

                <div style="margin-bottom: 50px;">
                    <div style="background: #f8fafc; padding: 35px; border-radius: 12px; border-left: 8px solid #00d9ff; margin-bottom: 40px;">
                        <h2 style="color: #0a192f; margin-top: 0; font-size: 2.2em;">üîê Need to Know Principle</h2>
                        <p style="font-size: 1.3em; margin-bottom: 20px; color: #0a192f;">
                            <strong>Definition:</strong> Access to sensitive information should only be granted to individuals who require that specific information to perform their job duties - regardless of their security clearance level.
                        </p>

                        <h4 style="color: #0a192f; font-size: 1.3em; margin-top: 30px;">Key Characteristics:</h4>
                        <ul style="font-size: 1.2em; line-height: 1.9;">
                            <li><strong style="color: #00d9ff;">Information-Centric:</strong> Focuses on protecting specific pieces of data or information</li>
                            <li><strong style="color: #00d9ff;">Purpose-Driven:</strong> Access is granted based on legitimate business purpose</li>
                            <li><strong style="color: #00d9ff;">Time-Limited:</strong> Access may be temporary, granted only for the duration needed</li>
                            <li><strong style="color: #00d9ff;">Compartmentalization:</strong> Even colleagues at the same level may not have access to each other's data</li>
                        </ul>

                        <div style="background: linear-gradient(135deg, #0a192f 0%, #112240 100%); color: white; padding: 25px; border-radius: 10px; margin-top: 30px;">
                            <h4 style="color: #00d9ff; font-size: 1.4em; margin-bottom: 15px;">Real-World Examples:</h4>
                            <div style="font-size: 1.2em; line-height: 1.9; margin-bottom: 20px;">
                                <p style="margin-bottom: 15px;"><strong style="color: #00d9ff;">Military/Government:</strong> A soldier with Top Secret clearance cannot access all Top Secret documents - only those related to their specific mission or assignment.</p>

                                <p style="margin-bottom: 15px;"><strong style="color: #00d9ff;">Healthcare:</strong> A nurse treating a patient can access that patient's medical records, but cannot browse records of patients they're not treating - even though they work in the same hospital.</p>

                                <p style="margin-bottom: 15px;"><strong style="color: #00d9ff;">Corporate:</strong> An HR employee processing payroll for the engineering department cannot access payroll data for the marketing department unless specifically assigned to work with that team.</p>

                                <p style="margin-bottom: 0;"><strong style="color: #00d9ff;">Legal Firm:</strong> Lawyers working on Case A cannot access files for Case B, even if both cases are handled by the same firm, to prevent conflicts of interest and maintain client confidentiality.</p>
                            </div>
                        </div>
                    </div>

                    <div style="background: #f8fafc; padding: 35px; border-radius: 12px; border-left: 8px solid #00d9ff; margin-bottom: 40px;">
                        <h2 style="color: #0a192f; margin-top: 0; font-size: 2.2em;">üéØ Least Privilege Principle</h2>
                        <p style="font-size: 1.3em; margin-bottom: 20px; color: #0a192f;">
                            <strong>Definition:</strong> Users should be granted the minimum levels of access - or permissions - needed to perform their job functions. Nothing more, nothing less.
                        </p>

                        <h4 style="color: #0a192f; font-size: 1.3em; margin-top: 30px;">Key Characteristics:</h4>
                        <ul style="font-size: 1.2em; line-height: 1.9;">
                            <li><strong style="color: #00d9ff;">Permission-Centric:</strong> Focuses on what actions users can perform (read, write, execute, delete)</li>
                            <li><strong style="color: #00d9ff;">Role-Based:</strong> Permissions aligned with job role and responsibilities</li>
                            <li><strong style="color: #00d9ff;">Default Deny:</strong> Start with no access and only grant what's necessary</li>
                            <li><strong style="color: #00d9ff;">Minimal Admin Rights:</strong> Limit the number of users with administrative privileges</li>
                        </ul>

                        <h4 style="color: #0a192f; font-size: 1.3em; margin-top: 30px;">Examples in Practice:</h4>
                        <div style="background: white; padding: 20px; border-radius: 8px; margin-top: 15px; border: 2px solid #00d9ff;">
                            <table style="width: 100%; font-size: 1.1em;">
                                <tr style="background: linear-gradient(135deg, #0a192f 0%, #112240 100%); color: white;">
                                    <th style="padding: 15px; text-align: left; border-radius: 5px 0 0 0;">Role</th>
                                    <th style="padding: 15px; text-align: left;">Access Granted</th>
                                    <th style="padding: 15px; text-align: left; border-radius: 0 5px 0 0;">Access Denied</th>
                                </tr>
                                <tr style="background: #f8fafc;">
                                    <td style="padding: 15px; border-bottom: 1px solid #ddd;"><strong>Data Entry Clerk</strong></td>
                                    <td style="padding: 15px; border-bottom: 1px solid #ddd;">Read & Write to assigned database tables</td>
                                    <td style="padding: 15px; border-bottom: 1px solid #ddd;">Delete records, modify database structure, access other databases</td>
                                </tr>
                                <tr>
                                    <td style="padding: 15px; border-bottom: 1px solid #ddd;"><strong>Developer</strong></td>
                                    <td style="padding: 15px; border-bottom: 1px solid #ddd;">Full access to development environment</td>
                                    <td style="padding: 15px; border-bottom: 1px solid #ddd;">No access to production systems or customer data</td>
                                </tr>
                                <tr style="background: #f8fafc;">
                                    <td style="padding: 15px; border-bottom: 1px solid #ddd;"><strong>Regular User</strong></td>
                                    <td style="padding: 15px; border-bottom: 1px solid #ddd;">Install approved software, access own files</td>
                                    <td style="padding: 15px; border-bottom: 1px solid #ddd;">No system configuration changes, cannot install drivers</td>
                                </tr>
                                <tr>
                                    <td style="padding: 15px;"><strong>System Admin</strong></td>
                                    <td style="padding: 15px;">Full system access for maintenance tasks</td>
                                    <td style="padding: 15px;">Should use regular account for daily work, admin only when needed</td>
                                </tr>
                            </table>
                        </div>
                    </div>

                    <div style="background: #fff3cd; padding: 35px; border-radius: 12px; border-left: 8px solid #ff6b6b; margin-bottom: 40px;">
                        <h2 style="color: #0a192f; margin-top: 0; font-size: 2.2em;">‚ö†Ô∏è Addressing Privilege Creep</h2>
                        <p style="font-size: 1.3em; margin-bottom: 20px; color: #0a192f;">
                            <strong>What is Privilege Creep?</strong> The gradual accumulation of access rights over time as users change roles, take on new responsibilities, or receive temporary access that is never revoked.
                        </p>

                        <h4 style="color: #0a192f; font-size: 1.3em; margin-top: 30px;">How Privilege Creep Happens:</h4>
                        <ul style="font-size: 1.2em; line-height: 1.9; color: #0a192f;">
                            <li><strong style="color: #ff6b6b;">Role Changes:</strong> Employee promoted from Sales to Sales Manager keeps old sales representative access + gains manager privileges</li>
                            <li><strong style="color: #ff6b6b;">Department Transfers:</strong> Employee moves from Marketing to Finance but retains access to marketing systems</li>
                            <li><strong style="color: #ff6b6b;">Temporary Projects:</strong> Granted special access for a 2-week project, access never removed after project ends</li>
                            <li><strong style="color: #ff6b6b;">Emergency Access:</strong> Given elevated privileges during an incident, permissions remain after incident resolution</li>
                            <li><strong style="color: #ff6b6b;">Poor Documentation:</strong> No tracking of why access was granted or when it should be reviewed</li>
                        </ul>

                        <h4 style="color: #0a192f; font-size: 1.3em; margin-top: 30px;">Dangers of Privilege Creep:</h4>
                        <div class="feature-grid" style="margin-top: 20px;">
                            <div style="background: white; padding: 20px; border-radius: 8px; border: 2px solid #ff6b6b;">
                                <h4 style="color: #ff6b6b;">üéØ Increased Attack Surface</h4>
                                <p style="color: #0a192f;">More permissions = more ways for attackers to exploit if account is compromised</p>
                            </div>
                            <div style="background: white; padding: 20px; border-radius: 8px; border: 2px solid #ff6b6b;">
                                <h4 style="color: #ff6b6b;">üö® Insider Threat Risk</h4>
                                <p style="color: #0a192f;">Disgruntled employees with excessive access can cause significant damage</p>
                            </div>
                            <div style="background: white; padding: 20px; border-radius: 8px; border: 2px solid #ff6b6b;">
                                <h4 style="color: #ff6b6b;">‚öñÔ∏è Compliance Violations</h4>
                                <p style="color: #0a192f;">Regulations require strict access controls; privilege creep leads to audit failures</p>
                            </div>
                            <div style="background: white; padding: 20px; border-radius: 8px; border: 2px solid #ff6b6b;">
                                <h4 style="color: #ff6b6b;">üí∞ Accidental Data Loss</h4>
                                <p style="color: #0a192f;">Users with unnecessary delete/modify rights may accidentally corrupt critical data</p>
                            </div>
                        </div>

                        <h4 style="color: #0a192f; font-size: 1.3em; margin-top: 30px;">Solutions to Prevent Privilege Creep:</h4>
                        <div style="background: white; padding: 25px; border-radius: 10px; margin-top: 15px; border: 2px solid #00d9ff;">
                            <ul style="font-size: 1.2em; line-height: 1.9; color: #0a192f; margin: 0;">
                                <li><strong style="color: #00d9ff;">Automated Provisioning/De-provisioning:</strong> Use IAM systems to automatically remove access when employees change roles or leave</li>
                                <li><strong style="color: #00d9ff;">Regular Access Reviews:</strong> Quarterly or bi-annual reviews of all user permissions</li>
                                <li><strong style="color: #00d9ff;">Role-Based Access Control (RBAC):</strong> Assign permissions based on roles, not individuals - easier to manage</li>
                                <li><strong style="color: #00d9ff;">Time-Limited Access:</strong> Temporary permissions automatically expire after a set period</li>
                                <li><strong style="color: #00d9ff;">Access Recertification:</strong> Managers must periodically certify that their team members still need current access</li>
                                <li><strong style="color: #00d9ff;">Least Privilege by Default:</strong> New employees start with minimal access, request more as needed</li>
                            </ul>
                        </div>
                    </div>

                    <div style="background: #f8fafc; padding: 35px; border-radius: 12px; border-left: 8px solid #00d9ff;">
                        <h2 style="color: #0a192f; margin-top: 0; font-size: 2.2em;">üìä Accountability Through Audits</h2>
                        <p style="font-size: 1.3em; margin-bottom: 20px; color: #0a192f;">
                            <strong>Why Audits Matter:</strong> Regular audits ensure that access controls are working as intended, identify violations, and maintain compliance with security policies and regulations.
                        </p>

                        <h4 style="color: #0a192f; font-size: 1.3em; margin-top: 30px;">Types of Access Audits:</h4>
                        <div style="margin-top: 20px;">
                            <div style="background: white; padding: 20px; border-radius: 8px; margin-bottom: 15px; border-left: 4px solid #00d9ff;">
                                <h5 style="color: #0a192f; font-size: 1.3em; margin: 0 0 10px 0;">1. User Access Reviews</h5>
                                <p style="font-size: 1.1em; margin: 0; color: #0a192f;">Review all user accounts and their assigned permissions to verify they're still appropriate</p>
                            </div>
                            <div style="background: white; padding: 20px; border-radius: 8px; margin-bottom: 15px; border-left: 4px solid #00d9ff;">
                                <h5 style="color: #0a192f; font-size: 1.3em; margin: 0 0 10px 0;">2. Privileged Account Audits</h5>
                                <p style="font-size: 1.1em; margin: 0; color: #0a192f;">Special focus on admin accounts, root access, and other high-privilege users</p>
                            </div>
                            <div style="background: white; padding: 20px; border-radius: 8px; margin-bottom: 15px; border-left: 4px solid #00d9ff;">
                                <h5 style="color: #0a192f; font-size: 1.3em; margin: 0 0 10px 0;">3. Activity Log Audits</h5>
                                <p style="font-size: 1.1em; margin: 0; color: #0a192f;">Examine who accessed what resources, when, and what actions they performed</p>
                            </div>
                            <div style="background: white; padding: 20px; border-radius: 8px; margin-bottom: 15px; border-left: 4px solid #00d9ff;">
                                <h5 style="color: #0a192f; font-size: 1.3em; margin: 0 0 10px 0;">4. Compliance Audits</h5>
                                <p style="font-size: 1.1em; margin: 0; color: #0a192f;">Verify adherence to regulatory requirements (GDPR, HIPAA, SOX, PCI-DSS)</p>
                            </div>
                            <div style="background: white; padding: 20px; border-radius: 8px; border-left: 4px solid #00d9ff;">
                                <h5 style="color: #0a192f; font-size: 1.3em; margin: 0 0 10px 0;">5. Orphaned Account Detection</h5>
                                <p style="font-size: 1.1em; margin: 0; color: #0a192f;">Identify accounts that haven't been used in X days or belong to terminated employees</p>
                            </div>
                        </div>

                        <h4 style="color: #0a192f; font-size: 1.3em; margin-top: 30px;">What Audits Should Verify:</h4>
                        <ul style="font-size: 1.2em; line-height: 1.9;">
                            <li><strong style="color: #00d9ff;">Principle of Least Privilege:</strong> Are users accessing resources beyond their job requirements?</li>
                            <li><strong style="color: #00d9ff;">Need to Know:</strong> Can users access sensitive data they don't require for their work?</li>
                            <li><strong style="color: #00d9ff;">Separation of Duties:</strong> Does any single user have conflicting permissions (e.g., create AND approve transactions)?</li>
                            <li><strong style="color: #00d9ff;">Dormant Accounts:</strong> Are there inactive accounts that should be disabled or removed?</li>
                            <li><strong style="color: #00d9ff;">Policy Violations:</strong> Are there any access patterns that violate security policies?</li>
                            <li><strong style="color: #00d9ff;">Anomalous Behavior:</strong> Are there unusual access patterns that might indicate compromise or misuse?</li>
                        </ul>

                        <div style="background: linear-gradient(135deg, #0a192f 0%, #112240 100%); color: white; padding: 25px; border-radius: 10px; margin-top: 30px;">
                            <h4 style="color: #00d9ff; font-size: 1.4em; margin-bottom: 15px;">Audit Best Practices:</h4>
                            <ul style="font-size: 1.2em; line-height: 1.9; margin-bottom: 0;">
                                <li><strong>Schedule Regular Audits:</strong> Quarterly for high-risk systems, annually for lower-risk</li>
                                <li><strong>Automate Where Possible:</strong> Use SIEM and IAM tools to continuously monitor and flag anomalies</li>
                                <li><strong>Document Everything:</strong> Maintain audit trails showing what was reviewed, findings, and remediation actions</li>
                                <li><strong>Assign Ownership:</strong> Managers should be accountable for their team's access rights</li>
                                <li><strong>Follow Up on Findings:</strong> Don't just identify issues - ensure they're resolved and track remediation</li>
                                <li><strong>Independent Review:</strong> Audits should be conducted by someone other than the system owner</li>
                            </ul>
                        </div>
                    </div>
                </div>

                <p style="font-size: 1.4em; text-align: center; margin-top: 40px; padding: 30px; background: linear-gradient(135deg, #0a192f 0%, #112240 100%); color: white; border-radius: 12px;">
                    <strong style="color: #00d9ff;">Remember:</strong> Security is not a one-time setup. Regular audits + proper access management = Strong defense against both external attacks and insider threats. Trust, but always verify!
                </p>
            </div>
        </div>

