        <!-- Slide 16 - Token-Based Authentication -->
        <div class="slide">
            <h1>Token-Based Authentication</h1>

            <div style="max-width: 1000px; margin: 0 auto;">
                <div style="background: linear-gradient(135deg, #0a192f 0%, #112240 100%); color: white; padding: 35px; border-radius: 12px; margin-bottom: 40px; text-align: center;">
                    <h2 style="color: #00d9ff; font-size: 2.5em; margin-bottom: 20px; border: none;">What is Token-Based Authentication?</h2>
                    <p style="font-size: 1.4em; margin-bottom: 0;">
                        An authentication method where users exchange their credentials for a <strong style="color: #00d9ff;">security token</strong> - a digital "proof of identity" that grants access to resources without repeatedly sending credentials
                    </p>
                </div>

                <h2>How Token-Based Authentication Works</h2>
                <div style="background: #f8fafc; padding: 35px; border-radius: 12px; border-left: 8px solid #00d9ff; margin-bottom: 40px;">
                    <div style="background: white; padding: 30px; border-radius: 10px;">
                        <h4 style="color: #0a192f; font-size: 1.4em; margin-top: 0;">The Token Flow:</h4>
                        <ol style="font-size: 1.2em; line-height: 2.2; color: #0a192f; margin-bottom: 0;">
                            <li><strong style="color: #00d9ff;">User Login:</strong> User submits credentials (username + password) to the authentication server</li>
                            <li><strong style="color: #00d9ff;">Credential Verification:</strong> Server validates credentials against the database</li>
                            <li><strong style="color: #00d9ff;">Token Generation:</strong> If valid, server creates a cryptographically signed token containing user information</li>
                            <li><strong style="color: #00d9ff;">Token Delivery:</strong> Token is sent back to the client (browser, mobile app)</li>
                            <li><strong style="color: #00d9ff;">Token Storage:</strong> Client stores the token (in memory, localStorage, cookies)</li>
                            <li><strong style="color: #00d9ff;">Authenticated Requests:</strong> Client includes token in every subsequent API request</li>
                            <li><strong style="color: #00d9ff;">Token Validation:</strong> Server validates token signature and checks expiration on each request</li>
                            <li><strong style="color: #00d9ff;">Access Granted:</strong> If token is valid, server processes the request</li>
                        </ol>
                    </div>
                </div>

                <h2>Token vs Session-Based Authentication</h2>
                <div style="background: white; padding: 25px; border-radius: 10px; margin-bottom: 40px; border: 2px solid #00d9ff;">
                    <table style="width: 100%; font-size: 1.1em; border-collapse: collapse;">
                        <tr style="background: linear-gradient(135deg, #0a192f 0%, #112240 100%); color: white;">
                            <th style="padding: 15px; text-align: left; border-radius: 5px 0 0 0;">Aspect</th>
                            <th style="padding: 15px; text-align: left;">Session-Based (Traditional)</th>
                            <th style="padding: 15px; text-align: left; border-radius: 0 5px 0 0;">Token-Based (Modern)</th>
                        </tr>
                        <tr style="background: #f8fafc;">
                            <td style="padding: 15px; border-bottom: 1px solid #ddd;"><strong>Storage</strong></td>
                            <td style="padding: 15px; border-bottom: 1px solid #ddd;">Server stores session data in memory/database</td>
                            <td style="padding: 15px; border-bottom: 1px solid #ddd;">Stateless - no server-side storage needed</td>
                        </tr>
                        <tr>
                            <td style="padding: 15px; border-bottom: 1px solid #ddd;"><strong>Scalability</strong></td>
                            <td style="padding: 15px; border-bottom: 1px solid #ddd;">Requires sticky sessions or shared session store</td>
                            <td style="padding: 15px; border-bottom: 1px solid #ddd;">Highly scalable - any server can validate tokens</td>
                        </tr>
                        <tr style="background: #f8fafc;">
                            <td style="padding: 15px; border-bottom: 1px solid #ddd;"><strong>Cross-Domain</strong></td>
                            <td style="padding: 15px; border-bottom: 1px solid #ddd;">Difficult - cookies don't work across domains</td>
                            <td style="padding: 15px; border-bottom: 1px solid #ddd;">Easy - tokens can be sent in headers to any domain</td>
                        </tr>
                        <tr>
                            <td style="padding: 15px; border-bottom: 1px solid #ddd;"><strong>Mobile Apps</strong></td>
                            <td style="padding: 15px; border-bottom: 1px solid #ddd;">Challenging - cookies not ideal for mobile</td>
                            <td style="padding: 15px; border-bottom: 1px solid #ddd;">Perfect - tokens work seamlessly with mobile apps</td>
                        </tr>
                        <tr style="background: #f8fafc;">
                            <td style="padding: 15px; border-bottom: 1px solid #ddd;"><strong>Performance</strong></td>
                            <td style="padding: 15px; border-bottom: 1px solid #ddd;">Requires database lookup on each request</td>
                            <td style="padding: 15px; border-bottom: 1px solid #ddd;">No database lookup - verify signature only</td>
                        </tr>
                        <tr>
                            <td style="padding: 15px;"><strong>Security</strong></td>
                            <td style="padding: 15px;">Vulnerable to CSRF attacks</td>
                            <td style="padding: 15px;">Less vulnerable to CSRF, but needs XSS protection</td>
                        </tr>
                    </table>
                </div>

                <h2>Common Token Types</h2>
                <div style="margin-top: 30px;">
                    <div style="background: #f8fafc; padding: 30px; border-radius: 12px; border-left: 8px solid #00d9ff; margin-bottom: 25px;">
                        <h3 style="color: #0a192f; margin-top: 0; font-size: 1.8em;">üîë JWT (JSON Web Token)</h3>
                        <p style="font-size: 1.2em; margin-bottom: 15px; color: #0a192f;">
                            The most popular token format. Self-contained JSON object with three parts: Header, Payload, Signature
                        </p>
                        <div style="background: #0a192f; color: #00ff00; padding: 20px; border-radius: 8px; font-family: monospace; font-size: 0.9em; overflow-x: auto;">
                            <div style="margin-bottom: 10px;"><strong style="color: #00d9ff;">Example JWT Structure:</strong></div>
                            <div style="color: #ff6b6b;">eyJhbGciOiJIUzI1NiIsInR5cCI6IkpXVCJ9</div>
                            <div style="color: #00ff00;">.eyJ1c2VySWQiOiIxMjM0IiwibmFtZSI6IkpvaG4gRG9lIiwicm9sZSI6ImFkbWluIn0</div>
                            <div style="color: #00d9ff;">.SflKxwRJSMeKKF2QT4fwpMeJf36POk6yJV_adQssw5c</div>
                            <div style="margin-top: 15px; color: white;">
                                <div><strong style="color: #ff6b6b;">Header:</strong> Algorithm and token type</div>
                                <div><strong style="color: #00ff00;">Payload:</strong> User data and claims (userId, name, role, expiration)</div>
                                <div><strong style="color: #00d9ff;">Signature:</strong> Cryptographic signature to verify authenticity</div>
                            </div>
                        </div>
                        <h4 style="color: #0a192f; font-size: 1.3em; margin-top: 25px;">JWT Benefits:</h4>
                        <ul style="font-size: 1.2em; line-height: 1.9; color: #0a192f;">
                            <li><strong style="color: #00d9ff;">Compact:</strong> Small size, efficient for HTTP headers</li>
                            <li><strong style="color: #00d9ff;">Self-Contained:</strong> All necessary info in the token itself</li>
                            <li><strong style="color: #00d9ff;">Stateless:</strong> Server doesn't need to store session data</li>
                            <li><strong style="color: #00d9ff;">Cross-Platform:</strong> Works with any language/framework</li>
                        </ul>
                    </div>

                    <div style="background: #f8fafc; padding: 30px; border-radius: 12px; border-left: 8px solid #00d9ff; margin-bottom: 25px;">
                        <h3 style="color: #0a192f; margin-top: 0; font-size: 1.8em;">üé´ SAML Tokens</h3>
                        <p style="font-size: 1.2em; margin-bottom: 0; color: #0a192f;">
                            XML-based tokens used primarily in enterprise SSO. More verbose than JWT but includes rich metadata and supports complex enterprise scenarios. Common in SAML 2.0 federation.
                        </p>
                    </div>

                    <div style="background: #f8fafc; padding: 30px; border-radius: 12px; border-left: 8px solid #00d9ff; margin-bottom: 25px;">
                        <h3 style="color: #0a192f; margin-top: 0; font-size: 1.8em;">üîê OAuth Access Tokens</h3>
                        <p style="font-size: 1.2em; margin-bottom: 0; color: #0a192f;">
                            Tokens issued by OAuth authorization servers. Can be opaque (random strings validated against server) or JWT format. Used for API authorization (e.g., "this token allows read access to Gmail").
                        </p>
                    </div>

                    <div style="background: #f8fafc; padding: 30px; border-radius: 12px; border-left: 8px solid #00d9ff;">
                        <h3 style="color: #0a192f; margin-top: 0; font-size: 1.8em;">üîÑ Refresh Tokens</h3>
                        <p style="font-size: 1.2em; margin-bottom: 0; color: #0a192f;">
                            Long-lived tokens used to obtain new access tokens without re-authentication. Stored securely, never sent with API requests. Enables "stay logged in" functionality while keeping access tokens short-lived for security.
                        </p>
                    </div>
                </div>

                <h2 style="margin-top: 50px;">Token Security Best Practices</h2>
                <div class="feature-grid">
                    <div class="feature-card">
                        <h4>‚è∞ Short Expiration</h4>
                        <p>Access tokens should expire quickly (15-60 minutes) to limit damage if stolen</p>
                    </div>
                    <div class="feature-card">
                        <h4>üîí HTTPS Only</h4>
                        <p>Always transmit tokens over encrypted connections to prevent interception</p>
                    </div>
                    <div class="feature-card">
                        <h4>üõ°Ô∏è Secure Storage</h4>
                        <p>Store tokens securely (httpOnly cookies, secure storage APIs, not localStorage for sensitive apps)</p>
                    </div>
                    <div class="feature-card">
                        <h4>‚úçÔ∏è Sign & Verify</h4>
                        <p>Use strong algorithms (RS256, HS256) to sign tokens and always validate signatures</p>
                    </div>
                    <div class="feature-card">
                        <h4>üö´ Token Revocation</h4>
                        <p>Implement token blacklisting or revocation mechanisms for emergency situations</p>
                    </div>
                    <div class="feature-card">
                        <h4>üìä Monitor Usage</h4>
                        <p>Log and monitor token issuance and validation for suspicious patterns</p>
                    </div>
                </div>

                <p style="font-size: 1.4em; text-align: center; margin-top: 50px; padding: 30px; background: linear-gradient(135deg, #0a192f 0%, #112240 100%); color: white; border-radius: 12px;">
                    <strong style="color: #00d9ff;">Key Takeaway:</strong> Tokens are like temporary digital badges - they prove you've already been authenticated without needing to show your password every time. Modern apps prefer tokens because they're faster, more scalable, and work better with mobile and microservices!
                </p>
            </div>
        </div>

        <!-- Slide 17 - Trust Relationships, SAML Tokens & SSO -->
        <div class="slide">
            <h1>Trust Relationships, SAML Tokens & SSO</h1>

            <div style="max-width: 1100px; margin: 0 auto;">
                <h2>ü§ù Trust Relationships</h2>
                <div style="background: #f8fafc; padding: 35px; border-radius: 12px; border-left: 8px solid #00d9ff; margin-bottom: 40px;">
                    <p style="font-size: 1.3em; margin-bottom: 20px; color: #0a192f;">
                        <strong>Definition:</strong> A pre-established agreement between two systems that allows one system to trust authentication performed by another system.
                    </p>
                    <h4 style="color: #0a192f; font-size: 1.3em; margin-top: 25px;">How Trust is Established:</h4>
                    <ul style="font-size: 1.2em; line-height: 1.9; color: #0a192f;">
                        <li><strong style="color: #00d9ff;">Certificate Exchange:</strong> Systems exchange X.509 certificates containing public keys</li>
                        <li><strong style="color: #00d9ff;">Metadata Sharing:</strong> IdP and SP share configuration metadata (endpoints, entity IDs, capabilities)</li>
                        <li><strong style="color: #00d9ff;">Configuration:</strong> Each system configures the other as a trusted partner</li>
                        <li><strong style="color: #00d9ff;">Cryptographic Validation:</strong> Tokens are signed with private keys and verified with public keys</li>
                    </ul>

                    <div style="background: linear-gradient(135deg, #0a192f 0%, #112240 100%); color: white; padding: 25px; border-radius: 10px; margin-top: 25px;">
                        <h4 style="color: #00d9ff; font-size: 1.4em; margin-bottom: 15px;">Real-World Example:</h4>
                        <p style="font-size: 1.2em; margin-bottom: 0;">
                            Your company (IdP) establishes a trust relationship with Salesforce (SP). Salesforce receives your company's certificate and metadata. When employees log in to Salesforce, it redirects them to your company's IdP, which sends back a signed SAML token. Salesforce validates the signature using your public certificate - if valid, it trusts the authentication and grants access.
                        </p>
                    </div>
                </div>

                <h2>üé´ SAML Tokens (Security Assertion Markup Language)</h2>
                <div style="background: #f8fafc; padding: 35px; border-radius: 12px; border-left: 8px solid #00d9ff; margin-bottom: 40px;">
                    <p style="font-size: 1.3em; margin-bottom: 20px; color: #0a192f;">
                        <strong>What is a SAML Token?</strong> An XML-based security token that contains assertions (statements) about a user's identity, authentication status, and attributes.
                    </p>

                    <h4 style="color: #0a192f; font-size: 1.3em; margin-top: 25px;">SAML Token Structure - Three Types of Assertions:</h4>
                    <div style="margin-top: 20px;">
                        <div style="background: white; padding: 20px; border-radius: 8px; margin-bottom: 15px; border-left: 4px solid #00d9ff;">
                            <h5 style="color: #0a192f; font-size: 1.3em; margin: 0 0 10px 0;">1. Authentication Assertion</h5>
                            <p style="font-size: 1.1em; margin: 0; color: #0a192f;">Confirms the user was authenticated, when, and how (password, MFA, biometric)</p>
                        </div>
                        <div style="background: white; padding: 20px; border-radius: 8px; margin-bottom: 15px; border-left: 4px solid #00d9ff;">
                            <h5 style="color: #0a192f; font-size: 1.3em; margin: 0 0 10px 0;">2. Attribute Assertion</h5>
                            <p style="font-size: 1.1em; margin: 0; color: #0a192f;">Contains user attributes (name, email, department, role, employee ID)</p>
                        </div>
                        <div style="background: white; padding: 20px; border-radius: 8px; border-left: 4px solid #00d9ff;">
                            <h5 style="color: #0a192f; font-size: 1.3em; margin: 0 0 10px 0;">3. Authorization Decision Assertion</h5>
                            <p style="font-size: 1.1em; margin: 0; color: #0a192f;">States what the user is authorized to do (optional, less commonly used)</p>
                        </div>
                    </div>

                    <h4 style="color: #0a192f; font-size: 1.3em; margin-top: 30px;">SAML Token Security Features:</h4>
                    <ul style="font-size: 1.2em; line-height: 1.9; color: #0a192f;">
                        <li><strong style="color: #00d9ff;">Digital Signature:</strong> Prevents tampering - recipient can verify token wasn't modified</li>
                        <li><strong style="color: #00d9ff;">Encryption:</strong> Sensitive attributes can be encrypted for confidentiality</li>
                        <li><strong style="color: #00d9ff;">Timestamp & Expiration:</strong> Tokens include validity period to prevent replay attacks</li>
                        <li><strong style="color: #00d9ff;">Unique ID:</strong> Each token has a unique identifier to prevent reuse</li>
                        <li><strong style="color: #00d9ff;">Audience Restriction:</strong> Token specifies which service provider it's intended for</li>
                    </ul>

                    <div style="background: #0a192f; color: white; padding: 20px; border-radius: 8px; font-family: monospace; font-size: 0.85em; overflow-x: auto; margin-top: 25px;">
                        <div style="margin-bottom: 10px; font-family: sans-serif;"><strong style="color: #00d9ff;">Simplified SAML Token Example:</strong></div>
                        <div style="color: #00ff00;">&lt;saml:Assertion ID="abc123" IssueInstant="2025-01-16T10:00:00Z"&gt;</div>
                        <div style="padding-left: 20px; color: #ff6b6b;">  &lt;saml:Issuer&gt;https://company-idp.com&lt;/saml:Issuer&gt;</div>
                        <div style="padding-left: 20px; color: #00d9ff;">  &lt;saml:Subject&gt;</div>
                        <div style="padding-left: 40px; color: white;">    &lt;saml:NameID&gt;john.doe@company.com&lt;/saml:NameID&gt;</div>
                        <div style="padding-left: 20px; color: #00d9ff;">  &lt;/saml:Subject&gt;</div>
                        <div style="padding-left: 20px; color: #ffff00;">  &lt;saml:AttributeStatement&gt;</div>
                        <div style="padding-left: 40px; color: white;">    &lt;saml:Attribute Name="email"&gt;john.doe@company.com&lt;/saml:Attribute&gt;</div>
                        <div style="padding-left: 40px; color: white;">    &lt;saml:Attribute Name="department"&gt;Engineering&lt;/saml:Attribute&gt;</div>
                        <div style="padding-left: 20px; color: #ffff00;">  &lt;/saml:AttributeStatement&gt;</div>
                        <div style="padding-left: 20px; color: #ff6b6b;">  &lt;Signature&gt;...digital signature...&lt;/Signature&gt;</div>
                        <div style="color: #00ff00;">&lt;/saml:Assertion&gt;</div>
                    </div>
                </div>

                <h2>üîê Single Sign-On (SSO)</h2>
                <div style="background: linear-gradient(135deg, #0a192f 0%, #112240 100%); color: white; padding: 35px; border-radius: 12px; margin-bottom: 40px; text-align: center;">
                    <h3 style="color: #00d9ff; font-size: 2em; margin-bottom: 20px;">What is SSO?</h3>
                    <p style="font-size: 1.4em; margin-bottom: 0;">
                        A user authentication process that allows users to access <strong style="color: #00d9ff;">multiple applications</strong> with <strong style="color: #00d9ff;">one set of login credentials</strong> and <strong style="color: #00d9ff;">one authentication session</strong>
                    </p>
                </div>

                <div style="background: #f8fafc; padding: 35px; border-radius: 12px; border-left: 8px solid #00d9ff; margin-bottom: 40px;">
                    <h4 style="color: #0a192f; font-size: 1.4em; margin-top: 0;">How SSO Works:</h4>
                    <ol style="font-size: 1.2em; line-height: 2.2; color: #0a192f;">
                        <li>User attempts to access Application A (e.g., Email)</li>
                        <li>Application A redirects to central SSO system</li>
                        <li>User logs in once to the SSO system (enters credentials)</li>
                        <li>SSO system creates a session and issues a token</li>
                        <li>User is redirected back to Application A with the token</li>
                        <li>User is now logged into Application A</li>
                        <li><strong style="color: #00d9ff;">Later:</strong> User tries to access Application B (e.g., Salesforce)</li>
                        <li>Application B redirects to SSO system</li>
                        <li><strong style="color: #00d9ff;">SSO detects existing session - no login required!</strong></li>
                        <li>SSO issues a new token for Application B</li>
                        <li>User automatically logged into Application B without re-entering credentials</li>
                    </ol>
                </div>

                <h2>üîÑ Identity Federation vs Single Sign-On</h2>
                <div style="background: white; padding: 25px; border-radius: 10px; margin-bottom: 40px; border: 2px solid #00d9ff;">
                    <table style="width: 100%; font-size: 1.1em; border-collapse: collapse;">
                        <tr style="background: linear-gradient(135deg, #0a192f 0%, #112240 100%); color: white;">
                            <th style="padding: 15px; text-align: left; border-radius: 5px 0 0 0;">Aspect</th>
                            <th style="padding: 15px; text-align: left;">Single Sign-On (SSO)</th>
                            <th style="padding: 15px; text-align: left; border-radius: 0 5px 0 0;">Identity Federation</th>
                        </tr>
                        <tr style="background: #f8fafc;">
                            <td style="padding: 15px; border-bottom: 1px solid #ddd;"><strong>Scope</strong></td>
                            <td style="padding: 15px; border-bottom: 1px solid #ddd;">User experience feature - one login for many apps</td>
                            <td style="padding: 15px; border-bottom: 1px solid #ddd;">Architecture/technology - how systems trust each other</td>
                        </tr>
                        <tr>
                            <td style="padding: 15px; border-bottom: 1px solid #ddd;"><strong>Focus</strong></td>
                            <td style="padding: 15px; border-bottom: 1px solid #ddd;">User convenience and experience</td>
                            <td style="padding: 15px; border-bottom: 1px solid #ddd;">Technical implementation and trust relationships</td>
                        </tr>
                        <tr style="background: #f8fafc;">
                            <td style="padding: 15px; border-bottom: 1px solid #ddd;"><strong>Domain</strong></td>
                            <td style="padding: 15px; border-bottom: 1px solid #ddd;">Usually within one organization/domain</td>
                            <td style="padding: 15px; border-bottom: 1px solid #ddd;">Across multiple organizations/security domains</td>
                        </tr>
                        <tr>
                            <td style="padding: 15px; border-bottom: 1px solid #ddd;"><strong>Goal</strong></td>
                            <td style="padding: 15px; border-bottom: 1px solid #ddd;">Reduce login fatigue, improve productivity</td>
                            <td style="padding: 15px; border-bottom: 1px solid #ddd;">Enable identity sharing, eliminate duplicate accounts</td>
                        </tr>
                        <tr style="background: #f8fafc;">
                            <td style="padding: 15px; border-bottom: 1px solid #ddd;"><strong>Example</strong></td>
                            <td style="padding: 15px; border-bottom: 1px solid #ddd;">Log in once to access Gmail, Drive, Calendar, YouTube</td>
                            <td style="padding: 15px; border-bottom: 1px solid #ddd;">Use your company login to access partner organization systems</td>
                        </tr>
                        <tr>
                            <td style="padding: 15px;"><strong>Relationship</strong></td>
                            <td colspan="2" style="padding: 15px; background: #fff3cd; text-align: center;"><strong>SSO is often implemented using Identity Federation protocols!</strong></td>
                        </tr>
                    </table>
                </div>

                <div style="background: linear-gradient(135deg, #0a192f 0%, #112240 100%); color: white; padding: 30px; border-radius: 12px;">
                    <h4 style="color: #00d9ff; font-size: 1.5em; margin-top: 0;">üéØ The Relationship Explained:</h4>
                    <p style="font-size: 1.2em; line-height: 1.9; margin-bottom: 0;">
                        <strong>Think of it this way:</strong><br><br>
                        <strong style="color: #00d9ff;">Identity Federation</strong> is the underlying technology/protocol (SAML, OAuth, OIDC) that establishes trust and enables identity sharing between systems.<br><br>
                        <strong style="color: #00d9ff;">SSO</strong> is the user-facing result - the ability to log in once and access everything.<br><br>
                        <strong>Analogy:</strong> Federation is like the railway infrastructure (tracks, signals, agreements between railway companies). SSO is like having a single train ticket that works on all trains in the network!<br><br>
                        <strong style="color: #ffff00;">You can have SSO without federation</strong> (all apps use same database), but <strong style="color: #ffff00;">modern SSO implementations typically use federation protocols</strong> to achieve seamless authentication across different systems and organizations.
                    </p>
                </div>
            </div>
        </div>

