                <h2>üéØ Key Differences Explained</h2>
                <div style="margin-bottom: 40px;">
                    <div style="background: #fff3cd; padding: 30px; border-radius: 12px; border-left: 8px solid #ff6b6b; margin-bottom: 25px;">
                        <h3 style="color: #0a192f; margin-top: 0; font-size: 1.8em;">‚ö†Ô∏è Critical Distinction: Authentication vs Authorization</h3>
                        <div style="background: white; padding: 25px; border-radius: 10px; margin-top: 20px;">
                            <p style="font-size: 1.2em; color: #0a192f; line-height: 1.9; margin-bottom: 15px;">
                                <strong style="color: #ff6b6b;">SAML & OIDC:</strong> Answer <strong>"Who are you?"</strong> - They authenticate users and prove identity
                            </p>
                            <p style="font-size: 1.2em; color: #0a192f; line-height: 1.9; margin-bottom: 0;">
                                <strong style="color: #00d9ff;">OAuth 2.0:</strong> Answers <strong>"What can you access?"</strong> - It authorizes access without proving identity
                            </p>
                        </div>
                        <p style="font-size: 1.2em; margin-top: 20px; color: #0a192f; margin-bottom: 0;">
                            <strong>Important:</strong> OAuth 2.0 is NOT an authentication protocol! Using OAuth tokens for authentication is a common mistake. That's why OpenID Connect was created - it adds an identity layer on top of OAuth.
                        </p>
                    </div>

                    <div style="background: #f8fafc; padding: 30px; border-radius: 12px; border-left: 8px solid #00d9ff; margin-bottom: 25px;">
                        <h3 style="color: #0a192f; margin-top: 0; font-size: 1.8em;">üîÑ OpenID Connect = OAuth 2.0 + Identity</h3>
                        <p style="font-size: 1.2em; color: #0a192f; line-height: 1.9; margin-bottom: 0;">
                            OIDC is built as a thin identity layer on top of OAuth 2.0. It uses OAuth's authorization flow but adds an <strong style="color: #00d9ff;">ID Token</strong> (JWT) that contains user identity information. This means OIDC can do both authentication (via ID Token) and authorization (via OAuth Access Token).
                        </p>
                    </div>

                    <div style="background: #f8fafc; padding: 30px; border-radius: 12px; border-left: 8px solid #00d9ff;">
                        <h3 style="color: #0a192f; margin-top: 0; font-size: 1.8em;">üì± Modern vs Legacy</h3>
                        <ul style="font-size: 1.2em; line-height: 1.9; color: #0a192f; margin-bottom: 0;">
                            <li><strong style="color: #ff6b6b;">SAML:</strong> Legacy protocol optimized for web browsers and XML. Still dominant in enterprise but being replaced by OIDC in new implementations</li>
                            <li><strong style="color: #00d9ff;">OIDC:</strong> Modern, designed for today's web, mobile apps, and APIs. JSON-based, simpler, better developer experience</li>
                            <li><strong style="color: #00ff00;">OAuth 2.0:</strong> Foundation for modern authorization. OIDC builds on it for authentication</li>
                        </ul>
                    </div>
                </div>

                <h2>Real-World Scenarios</h2>
                <div style="background: linear-gradient(135deg, #0a192f 0%, #112240 100%); color: white; padding: 30px; border-radius: 12px; margin-bottom: 40px;">
                    <div style="margin-bottom: 25px;">
                        <h4 style="color: #ff6b6b; font-size: 1.4em; margin-bottom: 10px;">üé´ Use SAML When:</h4>
                        <ul style="font-size: 1.2em; line-height: 1.9;">
                            <li>Implementing enterprise SSO for web applications</li>
                            <li>Integrating with legacy enterprise systems that require SAML</li>
                            <li>B2B federation where partner organizations use SAML</li>
                            <li>Compliance requires XML signatures and enterprise-grade security</li>
                        </ul>
                    </div>

                    <div style="margin-bottom: 25px;">
                        <h4 style="color: #00d9ff; font-size: 1.4em; margin-bottom: 10px;">üîê Use OpenID Connect When:</h4>
                        <ul style="font-size: 1.2em; line-height: 1.9;">
                            <li>Building new applications (web, mobile, SPA)</li>
                            <li>Need user authentication AND authorization</li>
                            <li>Want simpler implementation than SAML</li>
                            <li>Building consumer-facing applications (social login)</li>
                            <li>Need to access APIs after authentication</li>
                        </ul>
                    </div>

                    <div>
                        <h4 style="color: #00ff00; font-size: 1.4em; margin-bottom: 10px;">üîë Use OAuth 2.0 When:</h4>
                        <ul style="font-size: 1.2em; line-height: 1.9; margin-bottom: 0;">
                            <li>Need delegated API access (app accessing API on user's behalf)</li>
                            <li>Building third-party integrations ("Allow app X to access your data")</li>
                            <li>Machine-to-machine authentication (client credentials flow)</li>
                            <li>Authorization is needed but NOT authentication</li>
                        </ul>
                    </div>
                </div>

                <h2>Common Combinations</h2>
                <div class="feature-grid">
                    <div style="background: #f8fafc; padding: 25px; border-radius: 10px; border: 2px solid #00d9ff;">
                        <h4 style="color: #0a192f; font-size: 1.3em;">üîê OIDC + OAuth</h4>
                        <p style="color: #0a192f; font-size: 1.1em; margin-bottom: 0;">Most common modern setup. OIDC for authentication (ID Token) + OAuth for API authorization (Access Token)</p>
                    </div>
                    <div style="background: #f8fafc; padding: 25px; border-radius: 10px; border: 2px solid #00d9ff;">
                        <h4 style="color: #0a192f; font-size: 1.3em;">üé´ SAML for SSO + OAuth for APIs</h4>
                        <p style="color: #0a192f; font-size: 1.1em; margin-bottom: 0;">Enterprise approach. SAML for employee web SSO, OAuth for mobile apps and API access</p>
                    </div>
                    <div style="background: #f8fafc; padding: 25px; border-radius: 10px; border: 2px solid #00d9ff;">
