        <!-- Slide 33 - Asymmetric Cryptography -->
        <div class="slide">
            <h1>üîê Asymmetric Cryptography</h1>

            <div style="max-width: 1000px; margin: 0 auto;">
                <div style="background: linear-gradient(135deg, #f093fb 0%, #f5576c 100%); color: white; padding: 40px; border-radius: 12px; margin-bottom: 35px; text-align: center;">
                    <h2 style="color: white; font-size: 2.5em; margin-bottom: 20px; border: none;">What is Asymmetric Encryption?</h2>
                    <p style="font-size: 1.4em; line-height: 1.8; margin-bottom: 0;">
                        Also known as <strong>"Public Key Cryptography"</strong> - Uses a <strong>pair of mathematically related keys</strong>: a <strong style="color: #fff;">Public Key</strong> (shared openly) and a <strong style="color: #fff;">Private Key</strong> (kept secret). What one key encrypts, only the other can decrypt.
                    </p>
                </div>

                <div style="background: #fff3cd; padding: 30px; border-radius: 12px; border-left: 6px solid #f093fb; margin-bottom: 35px;">
                    <h3 style="color: #0a192f; font-size: 1.8em; margin-bottom: 20px;">üîÑ How It Works</h3>
                    <div style="background: white; padding: 30px; border-radius: 12px; margin-bottom: 20px; box-shadow: 0 2px 8px rgba(0,0,0,0.1);">
                        <h4 style="color: #f093fb; font-size: 1.4em; margin-bottom: 15px;">üîí Scenario 1: Confidential Message (Encryption)</h4>
                        <p style="font-size: 1.15em; color: #0a192f; line-height: 1.9; margin: 0;">
                            <strong style="color: #f093fb;">Alice wants to send Bob a secret message:</strong><br>
                            1Ô∏è‚É£ Bob generates a key pair: <strong style="color: #28a745;">Public Key</strong> + <strong style="color: #dc3545;">Private Key</strong><br>
                            2Ô∏è‚É£ Bob shares his <strong style="color: #28a745;">Public Key</strong> openly (anyone can have it)<br>
                            3Ô∏è‚É£ Alice encrypts "Meet at 3PM" using <strong style="color: #28a745;">Bob's Public Key</strong> ‚Üí Ciphertext<br>
                            4Ô∏è‚É£ Alice sends ciphertext to Bob<br>
                            5Ô∏è‚É£ Bob decrypts using his <strong style="color: #dc3545;">Private Key</strong> (only he has it) ‚Üí "Meet at 3PM"<br>
                            6Ô∏è‚É£ <strong>Key Point:</strong> Even if attacker intercepts ciphertext and has public key, they CANNOT decrypt without Bob's private key!
                        </p>
                    </div>
                    <div style="background: white; padding: 30px; border-radius: 12px; box-shadow: 0 2px 8px rgba(0,0,0,0.1);">
                        <h4 style="color: #f093fb; font-size: 1.4em; margin-bottom: 15px;">‚úçÔ∏è Scenario 2: Digital Signature (Authentication)</h4>
                        <p style="font-size: 1.15em; color: #0a192f; line-height: 1.9; margin: 0;">
                            <strong style="color: #f093fb;">Bob wants to prove he sent a message:</strong><br>
                            1Ô∏è‚É£ Bob creates message: "Contract approved"<br>
                            2Ô∏è‚É£ Bob "signs" message by encrypting hash with his <strong style="color: #dc3545;">Private Key</strong> ‚Üí Digital Signature<br>
                            3Ô∏è‚É£ Bob sends: Message + Digital Signature<br>
                            4Ô∏è‚É£ Alice decrypts signature using <strong style="color: #28a745;">Bob's Public Key</strong> ‚Üí Gets hash<br>
                            5Ô∏è‚É£ Alice computes hash of received message<br>
                            6Ô∏è‚É£ If hashes match ‚Üí Message is authentic and unmodified, and Bob definitely sent it (non-repudiation)
                        </p>
                    </div>
                </div>

                <div style="background: #f8fafc; padding: 30px; border-radius: 12px; border-left: 6px solid #28a745; margin-bottom: 35px;">
                    <h3 style="color: #0a192f; font-size: 1.8em; margin-bottom: 20px;">‚úÖ Advantages</h3>
                    <div class="feature-grid">
                        <div style="background: linear-gradient(135deg, #28a745 0%, #20c997 100%); color: white; padding: 25px; border-radius: 10px; box-shadow: 0 4px 15px rgba(40, 167, 69, 0.3);">
                            <h4 style="color: white; font-size: 1.4em; margin-bottom: 10px;">üîë Solves Key Distribution</h4>
                            <p style="font-size: 1.1em; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0;">
                                Public key can be shared openly. No need for secure channel to exchange keys.
                            </p>
                        </div>
                        <div style="background: linear-gradient(135deg, #28a745 0%, #20c997 100%); color: white; padding: 25px; border-radius: 10px; box-shadow: 0 4px 15px rgba(40, 167, 69, 0.3);">
                            <h4 style="color: white; font-size: 1.4em; margin-bottom: 10px;">üìà Scales Well</h4>
                            <p style="font-size: 1.1em; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0;">
                                Each user needs only ONE key pair. n users need only 2n keys total (vs n(n-1)/2 for symmetric).
                            </p>
                        </div>
                        <div style="background: linear-gradient(135deg, #28a745 0%, #20c997 100%); color: white; padding: 25px; border-radius: 10px; box-shadow: 0 4px 15px rgba(40, 167, 69, 0.3);">
                            <h4 style="color: white; font-size: 1.4em; margin-bottom: 10px;">‚úçÔ∏è Digital Signatures</h4>
                            <p style="font-size: 1.1em; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0;">
                                Enables authentication, integrity verification, and non-repudiation.
                            </p>
                        </div>
                        <div style="background: linear-gradient(135deg, #28a745 0%, #20c997 100%); color: white; padding: 25px; border-radius: 10px; box-shadow: 0 4px 15px rgba(40, 167, 69, 0.3);">
                            <h4 style="color: white; font-size: 1.4em; margin-bottom: 10px;">üîê Perfect Forward Secrecy</h4>
                            <p style="font-size: 1.1em; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0;">
                                Compromise of private key doesn't affect past communications (if ephemeral keys used).
                            </p>
                        </div>
                    </div>
                </div>

                <div style="background: #fff3cd; padding: 30px; border-radius: 12px; border-left: 6px solid #dc3545; margin-bottom: 35px;">
                    <h3 style="color: #0a192f; font-size: 1.8em; margin-bottom: 20px;">‚ùå Disadvantages</h3>
                    <div style="background: white; padding: 25px; border-radius: 10px; margin-bottom: 15px; box-shadow: 0 2px 8px rgba(0,0,0,0.1);">
                        <h4 style="color: #dc3545; font-size: 1.4em; margin-bottom: 10px;">üêå Computationally Expensive</h4>
                        <p style="font-size: 1.15em; color: #0a192f; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0;">
                            100-1000x slower than symmetric encryption. Requires complex mathematical operations (modular exponentiation, elliptic curve operations). Not suitable for encrypting large amounts of data.
                        </p>
                    </div>
