                    <p style="font-size: 1.3em; margin-bottom: 0;">
                        Based on complex mathematical problems that are easy to compute in one direction but nearly impossible to reverse
                    </p>
                </div>

                <div style="background: #f8fafc; padding: 35px; border-radius: 12px; border-left: 8px solid #667eea; margin-bottom: 30px;">
                    <h3 style="color: #667eea; font-size: 2em; margin-bottom: 25px;">üîë RSA (Rivest-Shamir-Adleman)</h3>
                    <div style="background: white; padding: 30px; border-radius: 12px; margin-bottom: 20px; box-shadow: 0 2px 8px rgba(0,0,0,0.1);">
                        <h4 style="color: #0a192f; font-size: 1.5em; margin-bottom: 15px;">Overview:</h4>
                        <p style="font-size: 1.15em; color: #0a192f; line-height: 1.8; margin-bottom: 15px;">
                            <strong>Most widely used</strong> asymmetric algorithm. Invented in 1977, still dominant today. Security based on difficulty of factoring large prime numbers.
                        </p>
                        <div style="background: #f8fafc; padding: 20px; border-radius: 8px; margin-bottom: 15px;">
                            <h5 style="color: #0a192f; font-size: 1.3em; margin-bottom: 10px;">Mathematical Basis:</h5>
                            <p style="font-size: 1.1em; color: #0a192f; line-height: 1.8; margin: 0;">
                                <strong>Easy:</strong> Multiply two large prime numbers (p √ó q = n)<br>
                                <strong>Hard:</strong> Factor the product back into original primes (n ‚Üí p and q)<br>
                                <strong>Example:</strong> 17 √ó 19 = 323 (easy), but given 323, finding 17 and 19 is computationally hard for very large numbers
                            </p>
                        </div>
                        <div style="background: #f8fafc; padding: 20px; border-radius: 8px;">
                            <p style="font-size: 1.1em; color: #0a192f; line-height: 1.8; margin: 0;">
                                <strong>Key Sizes:</strong> 1024-bit (deprecated), 2048-bit (minimum), 3072-bit, 4096-bit (high security)<br>
                                <strong>Speed:</strong> Slow - not suitable for bulk data encryption<br>
                                <strong>Security:</strong> Secure with adequate key size (2048+ bits)<br>
                                <strong>Quantum Threat:</strong> Vulnerable to quantum attacks (Shor's algorithm)
                            </p>
                        </div>
                    </div>
